data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and its fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire manual `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` construction **won't compile**. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
// .NET 10 — no expression tree needed
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

The `Action`-based overload lets you use normal C# control flow (`if`, loops, etc.) inside the setter lambda.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two sub-changes

**a) Sibling complex types with same property names get uniquified.**
`ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` will produce renamed columns (e.g., `Street1`). A migration will be generated.

**b) Nested complex types use the full path.**
`Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` now maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` (was `BillingAddress_City`).

**Fix:** Pin the existing column names explicitly so no rename migration is generated:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
    {
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
        // repeat for other properties
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
    {
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
    {
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
        {
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method on this interface now has an additional `string logCommandText` parameter. Your implementation won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← NEW: redacted SQL safe for logging
    {
        // Use logCommandText for log output (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Add the same `string logCommandText` parameter to every other method you implement on this interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).

---

**Summary:** The `ExecuteUpdateAsync` change is the big win — it eliminates ~15 lines of expression tree plumbing. The other two are mechanical signature/config fixes. After making these changes, generate a new EF migration to verify no unexpected column renames sneak in.
